text: -The touchpad worked when it arrived, however it did not have multi-touch enabled (two finger scrolling, zoom in/out), nor was there a way in the control setting to enable multi-touch. This took a while to fix, but my pain is your gain. If you google Samsung series 5 trackpad driver, and go to the link from the Samsung official website, then you can download and install a new driver. Then go to Control Panel> Hardware and Sound > Mouse Properties > TouchPad > Options and modify settings for multitouch as desired.

text: It was very important that I update this review after having used the computer for sometime now. In the middle of December after just 29 days of using the laptop, it died on me. I was unable to get it to start, only the power light was on and the other lights would not come on. I contacted Samsung over the phone and after going through the routine with the tech support they finally asked me to send it for repairs. A return label was emailed to me and I sent the laptop off to them. after about two weeks in early January

text: I was slightly dissapointed in a way that I was left without a laptop for 15 days and in my opinion Samsung should have given me a new one promptly. Nevertheless, I was very satisfied in the sense that they did not touch the hard drive or reformatted it but sent it back in the same condition, intact with all the changes I had done in terms of updating the existing system, installing software of my choice and customizing it. By leaving it intact it saved me a lot of hassle of going through the routine again.

It's fast, solid and easy to convert to Win 7.  I replaced the spinning HD with a Crucial M4 512 GB without problems and it blazes with one of the hottest CPUs available.  It's also got all of the connectivity I was looking for USB (2x2,2x3), VGA, network, HDMI and SD card.  All that in a fairly light package.
The speakers are not high fidelity but have adequate power.  IAll in all a great machine.  The final test will be reliability but I'll have to get back with you on that in a couple of years.

text: Update:  I ordered Win7 (ca $167), however, I was out of town for a week and did not install it right away.  During this time, there were a number of Win8 upgrades.  And, guess what, Win8 started working like it should have on day 1.  I can now download my email--that is a biggy.  There are other small things that are also working better.  Bottom line, I returned the copy of Win7 today.  I have no benchmarks, but the computer seems fast at boot-up and various operations.  At this point I am quite happy with this

The trackpad is quite large and accommodates multi-touch as well, making for quick zoom-in and out functions. With Windows 8 this feature seemed almost a requirement without a touchscreen. The wrist-rest is stout

Hitman Absolution I can only take it to high settings and my frames are generally 34 FPS.

During stress testing, The GPU's temperature maxed out at 68C in furmark for thirty minutes, while the CPU maxed out with 82C in Prime95 for thirty minutes. While gaming, I have not seen higher than 62C on the GPU, and 73C on the CPU. Personally, i'd like to see temperatures after re-pasting the thermal compound, but I don't plan on doing that for several months as I'd like to keep my warranty.

text: Despite the bulkiness of the G75VX, I appreciate the trade-off received in performance and cooler temperatures. It is also nice to see the new Kepler based 670MX. It may not be a 675MX or 680M, but I understand the compromise of speed, energy efficiency and temperature. Not to mention I need some reason to go back to my desktop every so often. As of now, I highly recommend the G75VX over an Alienware or Clevo-based mobile gaming platform.

text: As most know by now Kepler GPUs have a core limit that won't let you clock more than +135MHz on laptops, without doing modifications that will void the warranty or may harm your hardware if you don't know what you're doing. Anyway, the core on 670MX is good enough to play all the latest stuff in 1080p on Ultra and even go ahead and turn on MSAA or FXAA - it's not a surprise when you see that the chip is a GK104, which is also the chip that powers 675MX/680M/MX as well as desktop 660/Ti, 670 & 680 :)

text: One small sound issue is the instance when you plug or unplug audio-in or -out, like headphones or a mic from the laptop and you have your Windows taskbar set to "auto hide". Sometimes it will lock it in "visible" position preventing it from "hiding". Anyway, it can be resolved by simply plugging/unplugging again - this will make it hide properly. In the end I remember having the same on a Win7 Asus K53SV-A1, which also used the same sound card - it's more of an Windows issue than Realtek HD problem.

text: All in all this is an excellent laptop.  It performs very well out of the box.  If you want to make this thing even better for a little extra cash, replace the standard 1TB 5400rpm with a SSD and move the 1tb to the other bay.  Re-install windows to the SSD and this machine boots in less than 8 seconds.  Also to future proof a bit (or for bragging rights), install 2 x 4gb ram sticks in the 2 open slots on the bottom of the computer to 16 gigs total.  As of today, you can get a 64Gb SSD for about 80 bucks and 2x4GB Ram

With the SSD and the extra RAM you will have a powerful computer no mater what you decide to do with it.

text: Windows 8, ugh. This operating system is not the fault of the computer, so I can't blame the system for it. But be warned, if you're new to it, it has a learning curve. text: It's been several years since I've had a laptop computer. With the touchscreen it has the "hands on" feeling of a tablet where I can expand windows or text using my fingers or touching the spot where I want the cursor to

text: Features include USB 3.0, which is the newer standard and makes USB transfers extremely fast. Which usually isn't a big concern except for backing up onto an external hard drive. And with only 500GB of space on this computer, I'd definitely recommend an external if you're doing any multimedia. There's also an HDMI out, which is wonderful, but there's no VGA out, so if you're planning to use this for presentations you might need to get an adapter.

text: -Ineffective IO layout. The ports are all crammed together near the front of the laptop, meaning that only select, very slim usb plugs can be plugged in simultaneously, as they are right next to each other, as opposed to being spaced out or on top of each other. For a guy with a lot of usb accessories (external hard drive, mouse, cooling pad, etc), this is very bad news. This is a design that looks good on paper, but is not based on reality. Definitely would recommend a usb hub with this.

-beautiful backlit keyboard
-great screen
-great built-in speakers
-easy access to internal components
-touchpad

Cons:
-disgusting lid (weird design and glossy plastic)

-nvidia (would have preferred AMD graphics)
-no display port
-CPU loads in the 90s while gaming
-battery only 4400mAh (2.5-3hrs moderate usage)
-single 8gb ram stick (would have preferred dual channel)

text: After converting all my desktops and my Sony laptop to an SSD, I had forgotten just how slow a HDD really is.  Even though this comes with a 7200rpm HDD, it still is the one glaring weak spot.  Fortunately this MSI laptop does come with two mSata ports and from what I gather, they will accept either 128GB or 256GB mSata drives and will perform RAID 0 if you choose to use two drives.  Plan is to add an mSata drive to speed this process up.

text: What is bad about it is that it feels terrible. There are two built in click buttons on the bottom of the trackpad, where two separate buttons are on many other/older laptops. This design itself is not an issue but the tolerances they used for it are terrible. The touchpads moves up and down about 1/8" and make a sort of spring noise when released. Then, you push on it the rest of the way to click on the buttons themselves. It works perfectly fine, it just sounds terrible and feels a mushy due to the play in it.

text: The LED Indicator lights are just way too bright on the front of the laptop. The sleep light blinks bright and fast, annoying the hell out of you if you are in a dark room! From what I have read it is better than the Alienware 14 (uncustomized) at gaming...though again it doesn't really concern me.

text: Laptop would not boot up for no apparent reason.  Returned laptop to be repaired. This will be the fifth time I send the laptop in for repairs.

I am so much more productive now, which is another surprise.

text: I installed photoshop CS6 and tested out editing some raw files. text: Right out of the box, this computer feels very well constructed. The lid is brushed aluminum and does not flex like that of some other systems I have used in the past and that's reassurance that the screen will face less stress from being flexed. The hinge is nice and tight too, and from what I can ascertain so far it should hold up for a very long time. The overall system has a little bit of heft to it as well, feeling quite solid. I personally prefer a system that feels rugged, even if it weighs just a little more.

text: At its thickest this system is roughly an inch. This is great - it fits beautifully in my computer bag and leaves room for papers and folders with it in the same bag. This is a minor point, particularly if the user is going to leave this system on the desk all the time, but I find it to be a positive trait. Other systems I have used have been a snug fit in the bag and require a little more planning when packing for use on the go.

summary: Well-Balanced System for Business and Gaming Use

For $5, you get your Start button back along with a configurable

text: Maybe "three cheers" is corny, but I love this laptop. First, it is fast. Second, they actually fit a number pad onto a 15.6" computer without squeezing the main keyboard. Third, the screen is bright and sharp--just as sharp or more so than my MacBook Pro. In fact, in general this computer compares very favorably to the 15-inch MacBook, which had been my benchmark for quality and reliability.

text: The overall look and feel of this Toshiba Satellite is excellent. The metal body parts and color give it a quality look and suggest it will hold up well over several years of use. The keyboard in particular is very impressive to me. It is almost totally silent and very smooth action. It is lit up, so working in low light is a breeze. Even the sound is pretty decent. You won't get any heavy, table-bouncing bass, but the sound is relatively full, crisp, and clear, especially for laptop speakers. The computer runs fairly

I cannot imagine this model holding up in a bookbag or soft-side briefcase full of other stuff.

It's right in the middle in terms of solidness and durability.

text: The full-sized illuminated keyboard is a pleasure to type on. The touch pad is responsive and has just a tiny bit of friction to it that improves it's tactility. "Mouse clicks" for "selection" on it require just a very light tap as it is very responsive and sensitive to your touch. "Left-click/Right-click" is equally responsive and provide good tactile feedback (just a slight depression of the pad). Everything worked very intuitively and I had no trouble at all with usage of the touch pad.

text: Next, I tested the speed of each laptop performing a fairly demanding computing task.  I don't do gaming, but I do use my laptop to do audio and video editing.  I installed the newest version of a video editing program on each computer and had them edit and render (produce a finished video) the same project.  The Toshiba won the race, finishing the project in 7 minutes 19 seconds.  The Dell was fairly close, finishing in 7 minutes 59 seconds.  The HP lagged in at 9 minutes 12 seconds.  Again, the Toshiba clocked in tops.

text: It's obvious where the laptop got its design inspiration from, and on that note, the actual build is very reliable like its MacBook counterpart. One complaint I have is that the metal mesh vents on the bottom of the laptop are so close to the system fans that if you press on the mesh vents, they WILL stop the fans from spinning. The vents aren't flimsy, but if you're holding up your laptop with one hand with your thumb on top of the laptop and the rest of your fingers on the vent, you will probably press in the mesh

text: The trackpad feels like glass, and has that same smoothness as the macbook pro or surface book. It works well, gestures have worked fine, but it is NOT a clickpad. There are 2 dedicated mouse click buttons that are plastic and a bit loud, which makes it easier to drag and drop/select text but that is a matter of personal preference. Personally I'd have preferred a clickpad like on the stealth, but this is still top notch in terms of quality.

Although it worked fairly well it still got to be kind of slow running both Mac OS and Windows 10 at the same time all the time. It would make more sense to have one operating system that could do everything I need it to while using all 4 cores of my processor

text: 2) Keyboard - I loved the layout and feel of the MacBook Pro keyboard. I can't feel a difference with the Razer's keyboard. It is super quiet and easy to use, plus with Razer's software you can change the colors of the keyboard and even have different special effects. The only thing I didn't like about Razer's keyboard is that the backlighting only shows the function keys and not the special functions like Volume or Brightness control. in the dark I have to memorize which function keys are the sound, brightness, etc.

I also loved how when I did need to use Windows I could use Parallels or BootCamp. It was the perfect all in one OS. This was the hardest thing for me to give up. The only reason I did was for the gaming aspect of it. I had to use BootCamp to play most of the games I had on Steam. Hopefully Apple will put in NVIDIA's new Pascall cards in next year's MacBook Pro. I
